# Portal Data Integrity Rules

---

## 1. RLS Invariant

### SP-DB-01: Every portal table must have tenant_id + RLS

```typescript
// Ō£ģ Required on all portal tables
export const supplierCase = pgTable('supplier_case', {
  tenantId: uuid('tenant_id').notNull(),
  // ...
});
// + pgPolicy attached
```

Enforced by `gate-db-module.mjs`.

---

## 2. Case Timeline ŌĆö Single Storage Truth

### SP-DB-02: Timeline is append-only

`supplier_case_timeline` rows are **never updated or deleted**. Corrections
are new entries (type: `system`, content: "Correction to entry X").

### SP-DB-03: Timeline references source entities, not copies

```typescript
// Ō£ģ Timeline entry references source
{
  entry_type: 'message',
  ref_id: messageId,       // FK to supplier_message.id
  ref_type: 'supplier_message',
  content: { summary: 'Message from J.Smith' },  // summary only
}

// ŌØī Wrong ŌĆö full message body duplicated in timeline
{
  entry_type: 'message',
  content: { body: fullMessageText, attachments: [...] },
}
```

### SP-DB-04: No parallel timeline tables

There is **one** timeline table: `supplier_case_timeline`. Do not create
`supplier_message_timeline`, `supplier_document_history`, or any other
activity-stream table. Other tables remain source entities.

---

## 3. Payment Status ŌĆö Append-Only Facts

### SP-DB-05: Payment status is a fact table (never UPDATE)

`supplier_payment_status_fact` is append-only. To change status, insert a new
row. Previous rows remain as history.

### SP-DB-06: State machine ŌĆö no impossible transitions

Valid transitions (enforce in domain logic, test with property tests):

```
SCHEDULED ŌåÆ APPROVED ŌåÆ PROCESSING ŌåÆ SENT ŌåÆ CLEARED
     Ōåō          Ōåō           Ōåō         Ōåō
  ON_HOLD    ON_HOLD     ON_HOLD   REJECTED
     Ōåō          Ōåō           Ōåō
  (back to previous stage when hold lifts)
```

Never allow: `CLEARED ŌåÆ SCHEDULED`, `REJECTED ŌåÆ SENT`, etc.

### SP-DB-07: Source precedence

When conflicting stage updates arrive:
`BANK_FILE` > `ERP` > `MANUAL_OVERRIDE`

A bank file update overrides a manual override. Enforce at the service layer.

---

## 4. Proof Chain

### SP-DB-08: Chain position is strictly sequential per tenant

`chain_position` is a monotonically increasing bigint per `tenant_id`. No gaps.
Property test (SP-8022) asserts this.

### SP-DB-09: Required indexes for proof chain

```sql
-- Scoped verification (e.g., "all proof entries for case X")
CREATE INDEX idx_proof_entity ON portal_communication_proof
  (tenant_id, entity_type, entity_id);

-- Full-chain integrity check
CREATE INDEX idx_proof_chain ON portal_communication_proof
  (tenant_id, chain_position);
```

---

## 5. Case Lifecycle

### SP-DB-10: Case status transitions

Valid lifecycle:

```
DRAFT ŌåÆ SUBMITTED ŌåÆ ASSIGNED ŌåÆ IN_PROGRESS ŌåÆ AWAITING_INFO ŌåÆ RESOLVED ŌåÆ CLOSED
                                                                  Ōåæ          Ōåō
                                                                  ŌööŌöĆŌöĆ REOPENED
```

`CLOSED` ŌåÆ `REOPENED` is allowed (creates new timeline entry). `RESOLVED` ŌåÆ
`REOPENED` is allowed. Other backward transitions are forbidden.

### SP-DB-11: CASE ticket format

Auto-generated: `CASE-{TENANT_SHORT}-{YYYY}-{SEQ}`
Example: `CASE-AFD-2026-00142`

Enforced by `SP-1008` (Case ID generator). Never hardcode ticket numbers.

---

## 6. Bulk Upload

### SP-DB-12: Row fingerprint is deterministic

```typescript
fingerprint = SHA256(
  supplier_id + invoice_number + invoice_date + amount + currency + vendor_reference
);
```

Same invoice re-uploaded ŌåÆ same fingerprint. Used for dedupe detection.

### SP-DB-13: Dedupe policy is per-upload, not global

Each bulk upload specifies: `SKIP_DUPLICATES` | `UPDATE_DRAFT` | `REJECT_CONFLICTS`.
Default: `SKIP_DUPLICATES`.
